

1. The if Statement
This is your entry point. JavaScript evaluates the expression inside the parentheses. If it results in true, the code inside the {} executes.

2. The else Statement
The else block acts as the safety net. It handles everything that doesn't meet the if criteria.

3. The else if Statement
In JavaScript, if you have multiple specific conditions to check, you chain them. You can have as many else if blocks as you need.

4. Comparison Operators
To make these conditions work "perfectly," you need to know how JavaScript compares values. These go inside your if () parentheses:

Pro-Tip: In JavaScript, always prefer === over ==. It prevents weird bugs where the computer tries to guess if a string and a number are the same thing.

5. Logical Operators (The "And" & "Or")
Sometimes you need to check two things at once:

&& (AND): Both sides must be true.

if (isHungry && hasMoney) { ... }

|| (OR): At least one side must be true.

if (isSaturday || isSunday) { ... }

